  { q: `Do radicals always tell you the meaning of a character?`, a: `In about 80% of compound characters, the semantic radical gives a reliable clue to the meaning category. Characters with the water radical (氵) almost always relate to water or liquids. However, some radicals serve purely as phonetic hints rather than meaning indicators.` },
  { q: `Do radicals help with pronunciation?`, a: `Some characters include a phonetic component alongside the semantic radical. For example, in 妈 (mā, mother), 女 is the semantic radical (woman) and 马 (mǎ) hints at the sound. About 40% of common characters follow this pattern, though sound shifts over centuries reduce reliability.` },
  { q: `Should I memorize all 214 Kangxi radicals?`, a: `No. Focus on the 30-50 most common radicals first. These appear in thousands of everyday characters. Once you know them, less frequent radicals become easier to learn in context as you encounter them in new characters.` },
  { q: `What is the difference between a radical and a component?`, a: `A radical is the specific component used to classify a character in dictionaries — each character has exactly one radical. A component is any recognizable part of a character. A character may have 2-3 components but only one is its official radical.` }
